WEBVTT

1
00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:04.000
Please turn with me to Psalm 1.

2
00:00:04.000 --> 00:00:06.000
Psalm 1.

3
00:00:06.000 --> 00:00:11.000
We're starting a new series this morning in the book of Psalms.

4
00:00:11.000 --> 00:00:18.000
And Psalms is a book made up of 150 Hebrew poems.

5
00:00:18.000 --> 00:00:21.000
And these were written not only to be read, but also to be prayed,

6
00:00:21.000 --> 00:00:23.000
and even to be sung.

7
00:00:23.000 --> 00:00:28.000
And for thousands of years, they have been a faithful guide to God's people,

8
00:00:28.000 --> 00:00:30.000
leading them in prayer and in praise.

9
00:00:30.000 --> 00:00:33.000
And I hope they will be the same for us.

10
00:00:33.000 --> 00:00:38.000
And the plan at the moment is to make our way through all 150 of them.

11
00:00:38.000 --> 00:00:44.000
And as we work through them, we are going to probably maybe group some of them together,

12
00:00:44.000 --> 00:00:47.000
but the plan is to go through the entire book.

13
00:00:47.000 --> 00:00:51.000
So before you start working out the math in your head,

14
00:00:51.000 --> 00:00:55.000
let me also say that this will be a series that we will also pause

15
00:00:55.000 --> 00:00:58.000
and return to from time to time.

16
00:00:58.000 --> 00:01:02.000
So don't think we're going to go through all just back to back.

17
00:01:02.000 --> 00:01:05.000
And yeah, so we'll come back to it.

18
00:01:05.000 --> 00:01:10.000
And all in all, it will probably take a decade or more for us to work through that.

19
00:01:10.000 --> 00:01:14.000
And let me give you a couple reasons why I'm okay with that.

20
00:01:14.000 --> 00:01:16.000
And I hope you are too.

21
00:01:16.000 --> 00:01:23.000
One of those reasons is that we hope and pray that Trinity Fellowship will be around far longer than that.

22
00:01:24.000 --> 00:01:28.000
By God's grace, we're praying that we'll plant a tree, so to speak,

23
00:01:28.000 --> 00:01:34.000
a church that will be around for generations to come should the Lord tarry His coming.

24
00:01:35.000 --> 00:01:39.000
But also why I'm okay with it taking a long time for us to work through this book specifically.

25
00:01:39.000 --> 00:01:43.000
It might be different if we were in Job or something, but the Psalms,

26
00:01:43.000 --> 00:01:47.000
this is a way of us underscoring the importance of prayer.

27
00:01:48.000 --> 00:01:51.000
If this church is going to be built on a foundation that lasts,

28
00:01:51.000 --> 00:01:55.000
prayer must be part of that foundation.

29
00:01:55.000 --> 00:01:57.000
It is an essential part of that.

30
00:01:57.000 --> 00:02:00.000
And regularly, we're turning to the Psalms and coming to God,

31
00:02:00.000 --> 00:02:08.000
asking Him to teach us to pray and to pray again is going to be vital for us as a church,

32
00:02:08.000 --> 00:02:12.000
both for those of us who are sat here now and those who will be here in years to come.

33
00:02:12.000 --> 00:02:15.000
So let's begin by reading Psalm 1 together.

34
00:02:15.000 --> 00:02:18.000
I'm not going to invite you, we don't always do this, but let's stand together

35
00:02:18.000 --> 00:02:23.000
and we'll all read Psalm 1 with each other.

36
00:02:23.000 --> 00:02:24.000
Let's begin.

37
00:02:24.000 --> 00:02:29.000
Blessed is the man who walks not in the counsel of the wicked,

38
00:02:29.000 --> 00:02:35.000
nor stands in the way of sinners, nor sits in the seat of scoffers,

39
00:02:35.000 --> 00:02:38.000
but his delight is in the law of the Lord.

40
00:02:38.000 --> 00:02:42.000
And on his law he meditates day and night.

41
00:02:42.000 --> 00:02:49.000
He is like a tree planted by streams of water that yields its fruit in its season

42
00:02:49.000 --> 00:02:52.000
and its leaf does not wither.

43
00:02:52.000 --> 00:02:55.000
In all that he does, he prospers.

44
00:02:55.000 --> 00:03:01.000
The wicked are not so, but are like chaff, let the wind drives away.

45
00:03:01.000 --> 00:03:05.000
Therefore the wicked will not stand in the judgment,

46
00:03:05.000 --> 00:03:09.000
nor sinners in the congregation of the righteous,

47
00:03:09.000 --> 00:03:12.000
for the Lord knows the way of the righteous,

48
00:03:12.000 --> 00:03:15.000
but the way of the wicked will perish.

49
00:03:15.000 --> 00:03:17.000
This is the word of the Lord.

50
00:03:17.000 --> 00:03:21.000
Let's pray.

51
00:03:21.000 --> 00:03:24.000
Lord, I pray that you would open our eyes that we might behold

52
00:03:24.000 --> 00:03:27.000
wondrous things in your word.

53
00:03:27.000 --> 00:03:30.000
And as we behold them, Lord, I pray that you would change us

54
00:03:30.000 --> 00:03:34.000
more and more into the likeness of your Son Jesus.

55
00:03:34.000 --> 00:03:36.000
And Lord, I pray that you would help us to teach,

56
00:03:36.000 --> 00:03:41.000
that you would help us to pray as he prayed.

57
00:03:41.000 --> 00:03:44.000
We ask all this in his name. Amen.

58
00:03:44.000 --> 00:03:48.000
Well, given that the Psalms are a book of prayers,

59
00:03:48.000 --> 00:03:51.000
it might seem a bit unusual or surprising that it actually

60
00:03:51.000 --> 00:03:54.000
doesn't begin with a prayer.

61
00:03:54.000 --> 00:03:57.000
So it begins with Psalm 1 and 2, and these are a kind of a

62
00:03:57.000 --> 00:04:00.000
prologue that will then lead us into the prayers of the

63
00:04:00.000 --> 00:04:02.000
book of Psalms.

64
00:04:02.000 --> 00:04:05.000
All right, so Psalm 1 is part of that prologue.

65
00:04:05.000 --> 00:04:09.000
Eugene Peterson described Psalms 1 and 2 as kind of

66
00:04:09.000 --> 00:04:13.000
pre-prayers that put our feet on the path that goes from

67
00:04:13.000 --> 00:04:17.000
a non-praying world where we're habitually distracted

68
00:04:17.000 --> 00:04:20.000
and intimidated into the praying world where we come to

69
00:04:20.000 --> 00:04:24.000
attention and practice adoration.

70
00:04:24.000 --> 00:04:28.000
So prayer doesn't begin with us trying to get God's attention.

71
00:04:28.000 --> 00:04:30.000
If we're thinking about it in that way, we're thinking

72
00:04:30.000 --> 00:04:32.000
about it in the wrong direction.

73
00:04:32.000 --> 00:04:36.000
Prayer begins with God getting our attention.

74
00:04:36.000 --> 00:04:40.000
Peterson once again says, what is essential in prayer is

75
00:04:40.000 --> 00:04:43.000
not that we learn to express ourselves,

76
00:04:43.000 --> 00:04:47.000
but that we learn to answer God.

77
00:04:47.000 --> 00:04:53.000
So Psalm 1 prepares us to pray by putting this God before

78
00:04:53.000 --> 00:04:57.000
us and calling us to pay attention to him and see what

79
00:04:57.000 --> 00:05:01.000
he says to us about himself in his Word.

80
00:05:01.000 --> 00:05:06.000
Psalm 1 is also a path to blessing.

81
00:05:06.000 --> 00:05:09.000
As Psalm 1 begins with the word, blessed.

82
00:05:09.000 --> 00:05:11.000
Blessed is the man.

83
00:05:11.000 --> 00:05:15.000
By the way, Psalm 2 ends with the same kind of thing,

84
00:05:15.000 --> 00:05:19.000
calling us to see God's blessing once again.

85
00:05:19.000 --> 00:05:22.000
Now word blessed communicates a sense of happiness,

86
00:05:22.000 --> 00:05:26.000
a sense of well-being, of having received good from God

87
00:05:26.000 --> 00:05:30.000
and responding in light of that.

88
00:05:30.000 --> 00:05:34.000
When I tell the kids, maybe on a Saturday,

89
00:05:34.000 --> 00:05:36.000
I want everybody to get in the car,

90
00:05:36.000 --> 00:05:39.000
we're going somewhere, it's often that I'll then get

91
00:05:39.000 --> 00:05:42.000
a symbol, where are we going?

92
00:05:42.000 --> 00:05:44.000
And they're asking that question because they want to know,

93
00:05:44.000 --> 00:05:47.000
are we going somewhere that I am actually going to look

94
00:05:47.000 --> 00:05:49.000
forward to going or is this somewhere I'm going to have to

95
00:05:49.000 --> 00:05:53.000
endure going, please let me know where we are going.

96
00:05:53.000 --> 00:05:57.000
And when it comes to reading Scripture or praying to the Lord,

97
00:05:57.000 --> 00:06:01.000
I wonder what feelings come up for you when it comes to

98
00:06:01.000 --> 00:06:03.000
where you're heading.

99
00:06:03.000 --> 00:06:07.000
It might be a sense of apprehension or a sense of

100
00:06:07.000 --> 00:06:10.000
fulfilling a duty or it might even be a sense of dread

101
00:06:10.000 --> 00:06:13.000
based on past experience, you know, trying that out

102
00:06:13.000 --> 00:06:16.000
and kind of failing in that area.

103
00:06:16.000 --> 00:06:19.000
It's amazing that the book of Psalms begins with that word

104
00:06:19.000 --> 00:06:22.000
blessed because this is kind of setting the trajectory.

105
00:06:22.000 --> 00:06:25.000
It's saying here is where we are going.

106
00:06:25.000 --> 00:06:27.000
If we go where the Psalms are taking us,

107
00:06:27.000 --> 00:06:29.000
where the Lord is taking us through His word here,

108
00:06:29.000 --> 00:06:33.000
this is a place of blessing, a place of enjoyment.

109
00:06:33.000 --> 00:06:36.000
So it's helping us to not be apprehensive

110
00:06:36.000 --> 00:06:39.000
but to want where we're about to go.

111
00:06:39.000 --> 00:06:42.000
We are heading for blessing.

112
00:06:42.000 --> 00:06:46.000
And that life of blessing is put before us in the form of a man.

113
00:06:46.000 --> 00:06:48.000
Blessed is the man.

114
00:06:48.000 --> 00:06:50.000
So for the next few moments, what we're going to do

115
00:06:50.000 --> 00:06:54.000
is we're going to look at this man together, this blessed man.

116
00:06:54.000 --> 00:06:56.000
And we're going to look at three things.

117
00:06:56.000 --> 00:06:58.000
We're going to see who he is.

118
00:06:58.000 --> 00:07:00.000
We're going to see what he does.

119
00:07:00.000 --> 00:07:02.000
We're going to see what he resembles.

120
00:07:02.000 --> 00:07:04.000
Okay? So just walking through the Psalms.

121
00:07:04.000 --> 00:07:06.000
First of all, who he is.

122
00:07:06.000 --> 00:07:08.000
So we're just asking the question.

123
00:07:08.000 --> 00:07:13.000
When it says blessed is the man, who is that man who is blessed?

124
00:07:13.000 --> 00:07:16.000
Well, this man is put before us, we might say,

125
00:07:16.000 --> 00:07:19.000
as both a pattern and a signpost.

126
00:07:19.000 --> 00:07:21.000
So what do I mean by that?

127
00:07:21.000 --> 00:07:25.000
First of all, it's a pattern in the sense that he is a type of the congregation.

128
00:07:25.000 --> 00:07:28.000
So although the Psalm begins by speaking about the blessed man,

129
00:07:28.000 --> 00:07:30.000
when you look at the end of the Psalm,

130
00:07:30.000 --> 00:07:34.000
it's now talking about the congregation of the righteous.

131
00:07:34.000 --> 00:07:36.000
So what it's been saying about this man all along it,

132
00:07:36.000 --> 00:07:39.000
it actually speaks of God's people as a whole.

133
00:07:39.000 --> 00:07:43.000
So what is true of them is true of him and vice versa.

134
00:07:43.000 --> 00:07:47.000
Okay? Or what's true of him is true of them rather.

135
00:07:47.000 --> 00:07:50.000
This may make me think about when it comes to like,

136
00:07:50.000 --> 00:07:53.000
what's true of the blessed man being true of the congregation?

137
00:07:53.000 --> 00:07:56.000
I was thinking about sitting at a barber shop back in the late 90s.

138
00:07:56.000 --> 00:07:59.000
And then when you'd sit there, you'd see pictures of all these different men,

139
00:07:59.000 --> 00:08:01.000
or you'd have a book where you're flipping through and seeing like,

140
00:08:01.000 --> 00:08:03.000
well, which one do I want to look like?

141
00:08:03.000 --> 00:08:05.000
And so at the time, it was a great time for haircuts.

142
00:08:05.000 --> 00:08:09.000
You still had the kind of vanilla ice, you know, with a lightning strike through.

143
00:08:09.000 --> 00:08:10.000
I'm sure some of you had that.

144
00:08:10.000 --> 00:08:13.000
And then you had, I don't know, bowl cuts for in at the moment,

145
00:08:13.000 --> 00:08:16.000
if you wanted a, you know, Jonathan Taylor Thomas kind of bowl cut,

146
00:08:16.000 --> 00:08:20.000
or you had, if you were really cool, you could have bleached tips,

147
00:08:20.000 --> 00:08:23.000
or you could go all the way and have the Eminem look.

148
00:08:23.000 --> 00:08:25.000
My dad would have killed me had I done something like that.

149
00:08:25.000 --> 00:08:27.000
But you kind of say, okay, well,

150
00:08:27.000 --> 00:08:33.000
what is the man that I want to pattern how I look after?

151
00:08:33.000 --> 00:08:34.000
Okay?

152
00:08:34.000 --> 00:08:36.000
So here in the Psalm we have, here is the man.

153
00:08:36.000 --> 00:08:37.000
All right?

154
00:08:37.000 --> 00:08:39.000
But this man is put before us as a pattern.

155
00:08:39.000 --> 00:08:40.000
Okay?

156
00:08:40.000 --> 00:08:41.000
What is true of him?

157
00:08:41.000 --> 00:08:42.000
We want to apply to our lives.

158
00:08:42.000 --> 00:08:46.000
In other words, the path that he is on is the path of blessing.

159
00:08:46.000 --> 00:08:47.000
Right?

160
00:08:47.000 --> 00:08:49.000
That's what we want when we look at this man.

161
00:08:49.000 --> 00:08:55.000
But when we look at the man here in light of the whole of Scripture,

162
00:08:55.000 --> 00:08:59.000
we see an even greater depth when it comes to this man's identity.

163
00:08:59.000 --> 00:09:02.000
That's what I mean by saying that he is also a signpost here,

164
00:09:02.000 --> 00:09:05.000
because he's not just a type of the congregation,

165
00:09:05.000 --> 00:09:08.000
he's also a type of Christ.

166
00:09:08.000 --> 00:09:10.000
So he's pointing to Christ.

167
00:09:10.000 --> 00:09:15.000
So Psalm 1 and 2 are this kind of gateway that put a picture of Christ before us,

168
00:09:15.000 --> 00:09:18.000
before we actually enter into the Psalms.

169
00:09:18.000 --> 00:09:22.000
So if you've ever read on Lord of the Rings or seen the movies,

170
00:09:23.000 --> 00:09:25.000
so I'm going to nerd out for a second,

171
00:09:25.000 --> 00:09:29.000
but you've got this river that's going into the entrance of Gondor

172
00:09:29.000 --> 00:09:31.000
and they're kind of the fellowship or making their way down

173
00:09:31.000 --> 00:09:35.000
and as they're going down the river, they see these two huge statues

174
00:09:35.000 --> 00:09:41.000
kind of with their arm out and these are depictions of the kind of kings of old.

175
00:09:41.000 --> 00:09:43.000
And so in a similar way in the book of Psalms,

176
00:09:43.000 --> 00:09:48.000
you've got Psalms 1 and Psalm 2 putting a portrait of this king before us,

177
00:09:48.000 --> 00:09:50.000
this picture of a king.

178
00:09:50.000 --> 00:09:54.000
This is going to be explicit in Psalm 2 when we look at that together next week

179
00:09:54.000 --> 00:09:57.000
when it's speaking about Christ there.

180
00:09:57.000 --> 00:10:03.000
But I would also want to make the case that you can see that too in Psalm 1 as well.

181
00:10:03.000 --> 00:10:09.000
So for example, in Deuteronomy 17, we're told that a king who is righteous

182
00:10:09.000 --> 00:10:14.000
will be a king that will have his own copy of the law of God next to him.

183
00:10:14.000 --> 00:10:19.000
At all times he will be reading that day and night.

184
00:10:19.000 --> 00:10:21.000
And so as we read this Psalm together, what do we read about?

185
00:10:21.000 --> 00:10:27.000
We read that the blessed man is someone who meditates on the word of God day and night.

186
00:10:27.000 --> 00:10:30.000
So as we're reading what it says here about the blessed man, we have to think,

187
00:10:30.000 --> 00:10:36.000
well is there a king who has ever fulfilled this description perfectly?

188
00:10:36.000 --> 00:10:41.000
The answer will be, certainly not in the Old Testament when you look at all the kings that are there.

189
00:10:41.000 --> 00:10:45.000
We might think, is there a person in history who's ever fulfilled this?

190
00:10:45.000 --> 00:10:49.000
Well the answer is, yes there is. And it is Jesus.

191
00:10:49.000 --> 00:10:54.000
So Jesus is the blessed man of Psalm 1.

192
00:10:54.000 --> 00:10:58.000
So what it says about the blessed man really points us to Jesus.

193
00:10:58.000 --> 00:11:02.000
He fulfills what we see here. He is Lord.

194
00:11:02.000 --> 00:11:07.000
He is the Christ. He is the true King of God's people.

195
00:11:07.000 --> 00:11:10.000
And he is also our representative.

196
00:11:10.000 --> 00:11:14.000
So what is true of Christ is true of his congregation.

197
00:11:14.000 --> 00:11:18.000
Our righteousness is found in Jesus.

198
00:11:18.000 --> 00:11:22.000
A life of true blessing is found in Christ.

199
00:11:22.000 --> 00:11:25.000
So Ephesians chapter 1 verse 3.

200
00:11:25.000 --> 00:11:27.000
Remember that when we were in Ephesians?

201
00:11:27.000 --> 00:11:32.000
Paul was blessing God the Father, the Father of our Lord Jesus Christ,

202
00:11:32.000 --> 00:11:38.000
who has blessed us in Christ with every spiritual blessing in the heavenly places.

203
00:11:38.000 --> 00:11:43.000
So the life of blessing in the New Testament put before us is the life that's given to us in Jesus.

204
00:11:43.000 --> 00:11:46.000
That's where blessedness is found.

205
00:11:46.000 --> 00:11:49.000
So that's who the blessed man is.

206
00:11:49.000 --> 00:11:54.000
He's both Christ, but it's also the congregation of those who are in him.

207
00:11:54.000 --> 00:11:58.000
But notice also with me what the blessed man does.

208
00:11:58.000 --> 00:12:02.000
So this is a life that is given to us freely in Christ,

209
00:12:02.000 --> 00:12:09.000
but that's not to say that it is a passive life where we just kind of sit around and experience blessedness.

210
00:12:09.000 --> 00:12:16.000
It's an active life. It's a life where we trust and follow Christ.

211
00:12:16.000 --> 00:12:21.000
So if we're going to know a life of blessing where we enjoy God and what he has given to us,

212
00:12:21.000 --> 00:12:25.000
it will be a life of decisive action.

213
00:12:25.000 --> 00:12:31.000
So we see this and what the blessed man declines as well as what he delights in.

214
00:12:31.000 --> 00:12:34.000
So let's see this together. So what does he decline?

215
00:12:34.000 --> 00:12:40.000
Blessed is the man who walks not in the counsel of the wicked,

216
00:12:40.000 --> 00:12:47.000
nor stands in the way of sinners, nor sits in the seat of scoffers.

217
00:12:47.000 --> 00:12:55.000
Just to summarize this, the blessed man refuses to listen to and follow the ways of the world.

218
00:12:55.000 --> 00:13:01.000
You can see a downward progression here in terms of the danger that he's refusing.

219
00:13:01.000 --> 00:13:05.000
There's a downward progression. It could be pointing us to a downward progression

220
00:13:05.000 --> 00:13:11.000
and how it describes us even walking. So it starts off with walking and then standing and then finally sitting.

221
00:13:11.000 --> 00:13:19.000
But the main kind of downward spiral is moving from giving your attention to ungodly ways of thinking,

222
00:13:19.000 --> 00:13:28.000
ungodly philosophy, and then moving from our thinking to adapting to sinful ways of living.

223
00:13:28.000 --> 00:13:36.000
And then finally coming to a place of full kind of acceptance among those who scoff at the things of God

224
00:13:36.000 --> 00:13:42.000
because you're no different to them and even joining them in scoffing at the things of the Lord.

225
00:13:42.000 --> 00:13:49.000
This is a danger that we all face. This is why it is in front of us here in the psalm.

226
00:13:49.000 --> 00:13:55.000
It might come from peer pressure where you actually physically with somebody could be at school

227
00:13:55.000 --> 00:14:03.000
or could be with work colleagues or whatever, but it doesn't have to be interacting with somebody in person,

228
00:14:03.000 --> 00:14:07.000
especially when you think about this kind of age of information that we are in.

229
00:14:07.000 --> 00:14:13.000
So the counsel of the ungodly can come in the form of a podcast or a good YouTube channel

230
00:14:13.000 --> 00:14:17.000
or it could come in the form of an audiobook, right?

231
00:14:17.000 --> 00:14:22.000
So we get information from all different directions now or bombarded with it.

232
00:14:22.000 --> 00:14:30.000
The thing is if we are gorging ourselves on junk, at the very least we will not have an appetite

233
00:14:30.000 --> 00:14:36.000
for the things that are best. We won't be able to delight ourselves in the things of the Lord

234
00:14:36.000 --> 00:14:42.000
if our minds are full of everything else.

235
00:14:42.000 --> 00:14:47.000
So it's clear here, filling our minds with things of the world will hinder us from enjoying the blessings of God.

236
00:14:47.000 --> 00:14:50.000
So we read this in the New Testament, Romans 12, 1,

237
00:14:50.000 --> 00:14:54.000
Do not be conformed to the things of this world,

238
00:14:54.000 --> 00:15:00.000
but be transformed by the renewing of your minds, right?

239
00:15:00.000 --> 00:15:03.000
So from our way of thinking to our way of living.

240
00:15:03.000 --> 00:15:07.000
The life of blessing isn't just about what we receive but also about what we refuse.

241
00:15:07.000 --> 00:15:13.000
So what are we actually refusing to shape our thoughts in our lives?

242
00:15:13.000 --> 00:15:16.000
It's a worthwhile thing to think through, pray through.

243
00:15:16.000 --> 00:15:23.000
But also we see he doesn't just decline the world, he delights in the Word of God.

244
00:15:23.000 --> 00:15:26.000
So notice what happens next in verse 2.

245
00:15:26.000 --> 00:15:32.000
It says, But, so in contrast, his delight is in the law of the Lord.

246
00:15:32.000 --> 00:15:38.000
And on his law he meditates day and night.

247
00:15:38.000 --> 00:15:45.000
So the one who experiences God's blessing doesn't just refuse the temptations of the world

248
00:15:45.000 --> 00:15:48.000
and just kind of leave it at that.

249
00:15:48.000 --> 00:15:51.000
No, he replaces them with something better, right?

250
00:15:51.000 --> 00:15:54.000
So there's a kind of a self-denial that is involved here,

251
00:15:54.000 --> 00:15:59.000
but it's not self-denial kind of as an end in and of itself, right?

252
00:15:59.000 --> 00:16:02.000
We deny ourselves, yes, but that's not the end.

253
00:16:02.000 --> 00:16:06.000
We deny ourselves with something better in view, okay?

254
00:16:06.000 --> 00:16:11.000
So it's not just like I'm refusing to do some things and I'm just stepping into a life of self-denial,

255
00:16:11.000 --> 00:16:14.000
but rather I'm embracing something better, alright?

256
00:16:14.000 --> 00:16:17.000
So in that sense the problem isn't desire.

257
00:16:17.000 --> 00:16:23.000
It's what we're feeding our desires all on.

258
00:16:23.000 --> 00:16:27.000
So I love C.S. Lewis' weight of glory sermon.

259
00:16:27.000 --> 00:16:29.000
I've never read it. I'd encourage you to read it.

260
00:16:29.000 --> 00:16:32.000
There's a book called Weight of Glory that has it printed in there

261
00:16:32.000 --> 00:16:39.000
and there's a kind of famous quote from it that I think really summarizes this point of refusing some things

262
00:16:39.000 --> 00:16:42.000
but then delighting in God instead.

263
00:16:42.000 --> 00:16:43.000
He says this in there. He said,

264
00:16:43.000 --> 00:16:48.000
It would seem that our Lord finds our desires not too strong,

265
00:16:48.000 --> 00:16:50.000
but too weak.

266
00:16:50.000 --> 00:16:56.000
We are half-hearted creatures, fooling about with drink and sex and ambition.

267
00:16:56.000 --> 00:17:04.000
When infinite joy is offered to us, like an ignorant child who wants to go on making mud pies in a slum

268
00:17:04.000 --> 00:17:10.000
because he cannot imagine what is meant by the offer of a holiday at the sea,

269
00:17:10.000 --> 00:17:14.000
we are far too easily pleased.

270
00:17:14.000 --> 00:17:16.000
Do you see the picture there?

271
00:17:16.000 --> 00:17:20.000
We're settling for something small when God is offering something so much better.

272
00:17:20.000 --> 00:17:28.000
We're settling for the mud puddle when the Lord is offering us the holiday at the sea, so to speak.

273
00:17:28.000 --> 00:17:33.000
So the blessed man shows us where greater pleasures are found.

274
00:17:33.000 --> 00:17:37.000
They are found in the law of the Lord.

275
00:17:37.000 --> 00:17:39.000
It says he delights in the law of the Lord.

276
00:17:39.000 --> 00:17:43.000
So if you're wanting to know where is this greater pleasure to be found?

277
00:17:43.000 --> 00:17:45.000
It is found in Scripture.

278
00:17:45.000 --> 00:17:47.000
So it's found in...

279
00:17:47.000 --> 00:17:49.000
So it talks about the law here.

280
00:17:49.000 --> 00:17:51.000
Another way of saying that is the Torah.

281
00:17:51.000 --> 00:17:54.000
So these are the first five books of the Old Testament.

282
00:17:54.000 --> 00:17:58.000
And just kind of side note as a sort of introduction into the Psalms again.

283
00:17:58.000 --> 00:18:02.000
The Psalms are broken up into five different books.

284
00:18:02.000 --> 00:18:04.000
You've got the individual Psalms, five books,

285
00:18:04.000 --> 00:18:08.000
and it's done in a way that almost echoes the Torah, the law.

286
00:18:08.000 --> 00:18:12.000
So you've got the Torah is five books, and then you've got the Psalms has its five books as well.

287
00:18:12.000 --> 00:18:15.000
So it's being put before us here as the Word of God,

288
00:18:15.000 --> 00:18:17.000
just as they've relied on the Word of God in the Torah before,

289
00:18:17.000 --> 00:18:21.000
so we can rely on the Word of God in the Psalms as well.

290
00:18:21.000 --> 00:18:25.000
But why would he delight in the Bible?

291
00:18:25.000 --> 00:18:28.000
Well, it's because of who speaks to us in Scripture.

292
00:18:28.000 --> 00:18:34.000
Last week we saw God revealing Himself to His people in His Word.

293
00:18:34.000 --> 00:18:37.000
It's in His Word that we come to know Him.

294
00:18:37.000 --> 00:18:40.000
And the Lord is our ultimate joy.

295
00:18:40.000 --> 00:18:44.000
And He is the source of all blessing.

296
00:18:44.000 --> 00:18:48.000
And the blessings that last forever.

297
00:18:48.000 --> 00:18:52.000
And if they could delight in the Torah, man, we have something to delight in.

298
00:18:52.000 --> 00:18:56.000
A few days ago I was looking through some vinyl records,

299
00:18:56.000 --> 00:19:00.000
and I'm getting addicted to doing that at the moment, and it's Dan and Kate's call.

300
00:19:00.000 --> 00:19:04.000
So I was looking through these records, and I pulled out this record,

301
00:19:04.000 --> 00:19:06.000
and I thought, this looks really, really good.

302
00:19:06.000 --> 00:19:09.000
And I thought, this is way cheaper than it ought to be.

303
00:19:09.000 --> 00:19:11.000
And I was about to get it.

304
00:19:11.000 --> 00:19:15.000
And then I looked, and I saw a little sticker on it, and it said,

305
00:19:15.000 --> 00:19:17.000
Disc 2, missing.

306
00:19:17.000 --> 00:19:21.000
And so that was why it was cheap, because there was only one disc in this record.

307
00:19:21.000 --> 00:19:25.000
The other one was gone, so I put it away. I wasn't interested.

308
00:19:25.000 --> 00:19:27.000
Alright, so kind of a silly illustration.

309
00:19:27.000 --> 00:19:32.000
But here we've got, when the Psalms are being written, they've got Disc 1.

310
00:19:32.000 --> 00:19:36.000
And the blessed man is delighting Himself in what is here.

311
00:19:36.000 --> 00:19:40.000
But imagine only having the Law, only having the Old Testament Scriptures.

312
00:19:40.000 --> 00:19:45.000
But now we've got the whole thing, and it's not just that we've got twice as many verses to look at as they did.

313
00:19:45.000 --> 00:19:49.000
No, it's that we're living after Jesus came.

314
00:19:49.000 --> 00:19:52.000
So we now see what all this was pointing to.

315
00:19:52.000 --> 00:19:55.000
And so we can see all of this being fulfilled in Jesus,

316
00:19:55.000 --> 00:19:58.000
and all the blessings that we have been given in Him.

317
00:19:58.000 --> 00:20:01.000
If they could delight in the Law of the Lord,

318
00:20:01.000 --> 00:20:05.000
how much more can we delight in God's Word,

319
00:20:05.000 --> 00:20:11.000
by being Jesus there, by the power of His Spirit?

320
00:20:11.000 --> 00:20:17.000
So God has given us His Word to fuel our delight in Him.

321
00:20:17.000 --> 00:20:24.000
And it's our desire to know Christ more that drives us to add fuel to the fire.

322
00:20:24.000 --> 00:20:27.000
That we might come to see more of Jesus.

323
00:20:27.000 --> 00:20:29.000
But what does that look like practically?

324
00:20:29.000 --> 00:20:33.000
It says, on His Law, because He finds joy there,

325
00:20:33.000 --> 00:20:36.000
He meditates day and night.

326
00:20:36.000 --> 00:20:39.000
Or meditate, there just means to mutter.

327
00:20:39.000 --> 00:20:43.000
So you don't think of like Eastern meditation or something like that.

328
00:20:43.000 --> 00:20:49.000
So it's speaking God's Word kind of out loud to yourself.

329
00:20:49.000 --> 00:20:55.000
In the book of Isaiah, it actually uses the same word to describe a lion growling over its prey.

330
00:20:55.000 --> 00:21:01.000
So meditating on the Word involves having an appetite for it,

331
00:21:01.000 --> 00:21:06.000
continually mulling it over, meditating day and night,

332
00:21:06.000 --> 00:21:11.000
and getting it into your system, into your way of thinking in such a way that it shapes your thoughts.

333
00:21:11.000 --> 00:21:14.000
It changes your life.

334
00:21:14.000 --> 00:21:19.000
So continually mulling over God's Word.

335
00:21:19.000 --> 00:21:27.000
So could I just simply but directly encourage you to do something to get in God's Word daily?

336
00:21:27.000 --> 00:21:29.000
Read the Bible daily.

337
00:21:29.000 --> 00:21:34.000
We have such a privilege to have our own copies of God's Word to get into.

338
00:21:34.000 --> 00:21:37.000
And here we see that this isn't just like a...

339
00:21:37.000 --> 00:21:38.000
I'm not talking like legalism here.

340
00:21:38.000 --> 00:21:40.000
It's not a matter of like fulfill your duty.

341
00:21:40.000 --> 00:21:47.000
It's like there is so much delight that is there for us to be found in knowing the Lord.

342
00:21:47.000 --> 00:21:51.000
And if that's the case, why would we not want to come to God's Word each day?

343
00:21:51.000 --> 00:21:57.000
Like whenever it works for you, however it works for you, pull out a Bible, listen to it.

344
00:21:57.000 --> 00:22:03.000
But think it over and bring what you are listening to to the Lord in prayer.

345
00:22:03.000 --> 00:22:06.000
Even if the prayer is, I have no idea what I'm reading right now.

346
00:22:06.000 --> 00:22:08.000
Lord, please help me to read this.

347
00:22:08.000 --> 00:22:15.000
But allow God's Word to make him known to you.

348
00:22:15.000 --> 00:22:24.000
It's by the Word that his Spirit then opens our eyes to see more of the beauty and glory that is to be found in Jesus,

349
00:22:24.000 --> 00:22:26.000
that we might delight in him.

350
00:22:26.000 --> 00:22:28.000
So why would we not come to God's Word?

351
00:22:28.000 --> 00:22:31.000
We used to live pretty close to my in-laws.

352
00:22:31.000 --> 00:22:37.000
And I remember getting in the car with my father-in-law fairly often.

353
00:22:37.000 --> 00:22:41.000
And if I was getting in the car with him in the morning, I knew at some point in the conversation,

354
00:22:41.000 --> 00:22:46.000
he would say, you know, I was reading this morning in Exodus.

355
00:22:46.000 --> 00:22:47.000
And it was that part where...

356
00:22:47.000 --> 00:22:50.000
And he would start talking about what he was reading that morning.

357
00:22:50.000 --> 00:22:53.000
And there would be some mornings where I'd be like, did I read this morning?

358
00:22:53.000 --> 00:22:54.000
What did I read this morning?

359
00:22:54.000 --> 00:22:56.000
And there was a...

360
00:22:56.000 --> 00:23:01.000
I did feel a little bit of a pressure to, you know, not be the one who didn't read anything or couldn't remember what I read.

361
00:23:01.000 --> 00:23:04.000
But looking back at that time and how often that would happen,

362
00:23:04.000 --> 00:23:10.000
like what stands out most to me isn't that kind of that pressure to like not have something to say.

363
00:23:10.000 --> 00:23:11.000
That's not what stands out to me.

364
00:23:11.000 --> 00:23:18.000
What stands out to me is the example of somebody who is meditating on the Word of God day and night

365
00:23:18.000 --> 00:23:21.000
and allowing that to shape his thinking throughout the day.

366
00:23:21.000 --> 00:23:26.000
And that was just a real helpful influence in my life.

367
00:23:26.000 --> 00:23:32.000
So this isn't about keeping a rule but growing in a relationship, right?

368
00:23:32.000 --> 00:23:38.000
So how can you grow in a relationship with somebody that you don't know?

369
00:23:38.000 --> 00:23:42.000
And how can we come to know more of the Lord?

370
00:23:42.000 --> 00:23:48.000
This is what is driving us to his Word, who he is and the desire to know him more.

371
00:23:48.000 --> 00:23:53.000
All right, so let's finally look at what the blessed man resembles.

372
00:23:53.000 --> 00:23:57.000
All right, so he's delighting in the Word of God, meditating on it day and night.

373
00:23:57.000 --> 00:24:00.000
And so, what's he like?

374
00:24:00.000 --> 00:24:08.000
He is like, verse 3, a tree planted by streams of water that yields its fruit in its season.

375
00:24:08.000 --> 00:24:11.000
And its leaf also does not wither.

376
00:24:11.000 --> 00:24:15.000
In all that he does, he prospers.

377
00:24:15.000 --> 00:24:17.000
Let's pause there for a second.

378
00:24:17.000 --> 00:24:21.000
So he's like this tree planted by rivers of water.

379
00:24:21.000 --> 00:24:26.000
It's a bit like what we read about in Jeremiah chapter 17 at the start of the service.

380
00:24:26.000 --> 00:24:28.000
If you look at your worship guide there.

381
00:24:28.000 --> 00:24:31.000
So there the blessed man is the one who is trusting in the Lord.

382
00:24:31.000 --> 00:24:35.000
He is like a tree planted by water that sends out its roots by the stream.

383
00:24:35.000 --> 00:24:41.000
It does not fear when the heat comes for its leaves remain green and is not anxious in the year of drought.

384
00:24:41.000 --> 00:24:44.000
For it does not cease to bear fruit.

385
00:24:44.000 --> 00:24:50.000
So if you are united to Jesus and drawing from his Word, meditating upon it day and night.

386
00:24:50.000 --> 00:24:59.000
Your life with him and your fruitfulness isn't dependent on how harsh or pleasant the circumstances are of life.

387
00:24:59.000 --> 00:25:06.000
Rather, you are connected to a water source that is deeper than what is happening on the surface.

388
00:25:06.000 --> 00:25:09.000
It's connected to him.

389
00:25:10.000 --> 00:25:12.000
One of my favorite trees is a Baobab tree.

390
00:25:12.000 --> 00:25:14.000
I don't know if you've seen those in Africa.

391
00:25:14.000 --> 00:25:19.000
When you see a Baobab tree in West Africa, you'll see them out in the Sahel Desert.

392
00:25:19.000 --> 00:25:22.000
You've got these ginormous trees.

393
00:25:22.000 --> 00:25:30.000
You think how in the world is this tree still alive right in the middle of this desert?

394
00:25:30.000 --> 00:25:39.000
What you don't realize is that it has a root system that goes so far, way down deep into the ground.

395
00:25:39.000 --> 00:25:45.000
It's able to draw from sources of water that are far beyond the surface of the desert.

396
00:25:45.000 --> 00:25:50.000
When you look at that big trunk, it's able to store more water than a lot of trees can.

397
00:25:50.000 --> 00:25:58.000
It's drawing it and it's filled up with that water and it bears fruit when the season comes despite being in a desert.

398
00:25:58.000 --> 00:26:00.000
It reminds me of what is going on here.

399
00:26:00.000 --> 00:26:15.000
You might look on the surface and think, how could you have a life of blessing spoken of here when this or the other is going on in our world or in your life?

400
00:26:15.000 --> 00:26:30.000
It is found in being rooted and grounded in Jesus, in His Word, in a source that is beyond what can be stopped by the world.

401
00:26:30.000 --> 00:26:32.000
So it talks about a couple of things.

402
00:26:32.000 --> 00:26:34.000
One is the fruitfulness of the tree.

403
00:26:34.000 --> 00:26:40.000
Notice that when we're desiring God and drawing from His Word, the result is a life of fruitfulness.

404
00:26:40.000 --> 00:26:48.000
He's like a tree planted by streams of water, so that's being rooted in the Word that yields its fruit in its seasons.

405
00:26:48.000 --> 00:26:50.000
Its leaf also does not wither.

406
00:26:50.000 --> 00:26:53.000
So there's a picture of fruitfulness there.

407
00:26:53.000 --> 00:27:03.000
So when we're rooted in Christ, drawing from His Word, God in his timing patiently brings about the fruit of His righteousness in our lives.

408
00:27:03.000 --> 00:27:06.000
So we're like an evergreen whose leaf does not wither.

409
00:27:06.000 --> 00:27:15.000
So there's a sense in which, in terms of like the evergreen side of it here, that He is our continual source of life.

410
00:27:15.000 --> 00:27:19.000
And yet there's fruitfulness that comes in its season as well.

411
00:27:19.000 --> 00:27:29.000
I don't want to read too much into the word season there, but if you're like me and the rest of us around, all the fruit doesn't all come at once.

412
00:27:29.000 --> 00:27:37.000
So it's over time that we are being shaped into the lightness of Christ, bringing forth fruit in season.

413
00:27:37.000 --> 00:27:41.000
It also speaks of prosperity here.

414
00:27:41.000 --> 00:27:45.000
In all that He does, He prospers.

415
00:27:45.000 --> 00:27:50.000
You also find this in the book of Joshua, right before leading God's people into the Promised Land.

416
00:27:50.000 --> 00:27:52.000
God says to Joshua, Joshua 1-8,

417
00:27:52.000 --> 00:27:59.000
This book of the law shall not depart from your mouth, but you shall meditate upon it day and night,

418
00:27:59.000 --> 00:28:10.000
so that you may be careful to do according to all that is written in it, for then you will make your way prosperous, and you will have good success.

419
00:28:10.000 --> 00:28:17.000
So what is the prosperity and success that we are promised?

420
00:28:17.000 --> 00:28:23.000
What's promised is if you give me your credit card information before the end of the service, there's a life of blessing that is coming to you financially,

421
00:28:23.000 --> 00:28:27.000
and you're going to have 10 times the amount of whatever you...

422
00:28:27.000 --> 00:28:29.000
We hear that on TV, don't we?

423
00:28:29.000 --> 00:28:32.000
What is the prosperity spoken of here?

424
00:28:32.000 --> 00:28:33.000
It's not that.

425
00:28:33.000 --> 00:28:41.000
In Psalms, actually, we see that material prosperity is not a fateful measure of success.

426
00:28:41.000 --> 00:28:47.000
Now, we can be guided by the wisdom of God's Word, and there can be times when that leads to some kind of material prosperity.

427
00:28:47.000 --> 00:28:49.000
Everything is in the Lord's hands.

428
00:28:49.000 --> 00:28:52.000
We can give Him thanks for anything He gives us, and we ought to.

429
00:28:52.000 --> 00:28:58.000
But material prosperity is not a fateful measure of success.

430
00:28:58.000 --> 00:29:02.000
So Psalm 73 is a great Psalm to look at.

431
00:29:02.000 --> 00:29:07.000
Psalmist talks about how he was envying the prosperity of the wicked around him.

432
00:29:07.000 --> 00:29:11.000
He's like, I'm living this life of faithfulness to the Lord, righteousness.

433
00:29:11.000 --> 00:29:16.000
And I'm not doing so well, and the world around me seems to be really prosperous.

434
00:29:16.000 --> 00:29:18.000
He was envying the wicked.

435
00:29:18.000 --> 00:29:26.000
But he says by the end, I'm not doing that anymore, and the reason he's not doing that anymore is because he sees their end.

436
00:29:26.000 --> 00:29:33.000
He sees that the prosperity that they are enjoying is temporary prosperity.

437
00:29:33.000 --> 00:29:39.000
The reality is though they're enjoying prosperity, now that is all the prosperity that they enjoy,

438
00:29:39.000 --> 00:29:44.000
but they will enjoy because they are heading ultimately for destruction.

439
00:29:44.000 --> 00:29:50.000
But when he thinks about his end, even though he doesn't enjoy the same kind of material prosperity here,

440
00:29:50.000 --> 00:29:56.000
he's thinking about my end is a life where I know God as my portion forever.

441
00:29:56.000 --> 00:30:01.000
And God is enough, and life with him goes on forever.

442
00:30:01.000 --> 00:30:03.000
Nothing can take that away.

443
00:30:03.000 --> 00:30:07.000
The blessings that I find in him are eternal blessings.

444
00:30:07.000 --> 00:30:13.000
So the greatest prosperity is prosperity that lasts eternally.

445
00:30:13.000 --> 00:30:17.000
If everything is taken away, you can't take that away.

446
00:30:17.000 --> 00:30:21.000
So the greatest success is doing the will of God.

447
00:30:22.000 --> 00:30:32.000
The greatest prosperity is receiving all of those blessings that are given to us in Christ that we read about in like in Ephesians 1.

448
00:30:32.000 --> 00:30:37.000
So prospering in everything is doing everything by him and for him.

449
00:30:37.000 --> 00:30:41.000
It is knowing his help and blessing in every area of life.

450
00:30:41.000 --> 00:30:45.000
It is bearing the fruit of his spirit.

451
00:30:45.000 --> 00:30:49.000
That is a work that lasts forever.

452
00:30:49.000 --> 00:30:54.000
We see that also in how it speaks here because it speaks not just of the fruitfulness of the tree,

453
00:30:54.000 --> 00:30:57.000
but also where it's heading in the future.

454
00:30:57.000 --> 00:30:59.000
Notice what it describes.

455
00:30:59.000 --> 00:31:09.000
It says in verse 4, the ungodly are not so, or the wicked are not so, but are like the chaff which the wind drives away.

456
00:31:09.000 --> 00:31:17.000
So if the godly are like this tree that is planted, the ungodly are like chaff that the wind is going to drive away.

457
00:31:17.000 --> 00:31:25.000
So the image of kind of winnowing is being used here where like grain is tossed up in a bit of a wind and when it's tossed up,

458
00:31:25.000 --> 00:31:29.000
the chaff is blown away and the grain then drops.

459
00:31:29.000 --> 00:31:31.000
So this is what is happening with the ungodly.

460
00:31:31.000 --> 00:31:35.000
They are like the chaff that the wind easily blows away.

461
00:31:35.000 --> 00:31:42.000
Things might feel okay now, but the reality is judgment is coming.

462
00:31:43.000 --> 00:31:48.000
There is a day when we will all stand before God and give Him an account.

463
00:31:48.000 --> 00:31:54.000
On that day there will be those who may be appeared to be stable and prosperous in this life,

464
00:31:54.000 --> 00:31:57.000
but in the end we'll lose everything.

465
00:31:57.000 --> 00:32:03.000
We will not stand on that day of judgment.

466
00:32:03.000 --> 00:32:09.000
Therefore, verse 5, the wicked will not stand in the judgment,

467
00:32:09.000 --> 00:32:14.000
but the sinners in the congregation of the righteous, for the Lord knows the way of the righteous,

468
00:32:14.000 --> 00:32:20.000
but the way of the wicked will perish.

469
00:32:20.000 --> 00:32:27.000
So people need to ask themselves like, is the thing that I'm living for going to matter in eternity?

470
00:32:27.000 --> 00:32:36.000
Is the prosperity I'm aiming for, the success I'm aiming for, is that going to matter ultimately on the day of judgment?

471
00:32:36.000 --> 00:32:40.000
So in the Psalm you've got this kind of reversal at the end.

472
00:32:40.000 --> 00:32:50.000
Those who are once standing with the world in its ways will not then stand on the day of judgment.

473
00:32:50.000 --> 00:32:57.000
Those who found that kind of place of belonging sitting among the scoffers will not find a place of belonging

474
00:32:57.000 --> 00:33:04.000
where it matters most in the end when God dwells with His people forever.

475
00:33:04.000 --> 00:33:08.000
In that place where in His presence there is fullness of joy.

476
00:33:08.000 --> 00:33:14.000
And that is right hand, there are pleasures ever more. That's the place where it counts.

477
00:33:14.000 --> 00:33:21.000
So these two ways are put before us here in stark contrast right the way through the entire Psalm really.

478
00:33:21.000 --> 00:33:26.000
One is a road that leads to destruction away from the presence of the Lord.

479
00:33:26.000 --> 00:33:31.000
The other is a road of blessing and life with God forever.

480
00:33:31.000 --> 00:33:35.000
So the question is kind of put before us like which road are we on?

481
00:33:35.000 --> 00:33:40.000
Are we on the road of that which will not last forever?

482
00:33:40.000 --> 00:33:45.000
Are we on the road with the Lord leading to this eternal blessing?

483
00:33:45.000 --> 00:33:51.000
So 1 John chapter 2 and verse 17 says this, the world is passing away,

484
00:33:51.000 --> 00:33:59.000
but he who does the will of God abides forever.

485
00:33:59.000 --> 00:34:06.000
So the thing that determines which of those roads you are on is whether or not you know the Lord now.

486
00:34:06.000 --> 00:34:12.000
Whether or not you know him and are with him then will be whether or not you know him now.

487
00:34:12.000 --> 00:34:17.000
So what does it say for the Lord knows the way of the righteous?

488
00:34:17.000 --> 00:34:24.000
Knows, the knowledge here that's spoken of is that it's an intimate relational knowledge.

489
00:34:24.000 --> 00:34:30.000
It is a relational knowledge of the Lord and his relationship to us.

490
00:34:30.000 --> 00:34:37.000
So does those who have a relationship with the Lord who will know the blessing of being with him forever?

491
00:34:37.000 --> 00:34:42.000
So we need to ask the question, well how can we then know him?

492
00:34:42.000 --> 00:34:44.000
How do we know the Lord?

493
00:34:44.000 --> 00:34:47.000
How do we know him as our source of life and blessing?

494
00:34:47.000 --> 00:34:52.000
The answer is through faith in the blessed man.

495
00:34:52.000 --> 00:34:56.000
Jesus, are we in him?

496
00:34:56.000 --> 00:35:00.000
So let's allow this Psalm to do its work in us.

497
00:35:00.000 --> 00:35:05.000
Point us to see Jesus and to see more of him in his word.

498
00:35:05.000 --> 00:35:08.000
To put our faith in him.

499
00:35:08.000 --> 00:35:12.000
And to find him to be our greatest joy.

500
00:35:12.000 --> 00:35:14.000
So let's pray together.

501
00:35:18.000 --> 00:35:31.000
Well thank you so much for giving us your word which points us to this life of a blessing that lasts forever.

502
00:35:31.000 --> 00:35:36.000
A blessing of knowing you and enjoying you forever.

503
00:35:36.000 --> 00:35:45.000
So Lord I pray that you would help us to turn our eyes away from those things that will not last in the end.

504
00:35:45.000 --> 00:35:50.000
And to fix our eyes on Jesus above all else.

505
00:35:50.000 --> 00:36:00.000
Lord I pray that you would give us a hunger for him and a desire for him that is stronger than our desire for anything else.

506
00:36:00.000 --> 00:36:07.000
And Lord I pray that as we desire him, Lord I pray that you would help us to put our trust in him.

507
00:36:07.000 --> 00:36:14.000
Lord I pray that you would help us to know you more and more and to trust you more and more.

508
00:36:14.000 --> 00:36:25.000
Lord I pray that you would help us to be a people who are coming to your word day and night that we might see more and more of you.

509
00:36:25.000 --> 00:36:34.000
Lord I thank you that what we see in you and the blessings that we receive from you will last forever and forever.

510
00:36:34.000 --> 00:36:39.000
So Lord I pray that you would help us to trust in you.

511
00:36:39.000 --> 00:36:43.000
It's another blessing of being in Christ.

512
00:36:43.000 --> 00:36:50.000
Lord I pray that as we are in him and growing in him together that you would make us a people of prayer.

513
00:36:50.000 --> 00:36:53.000
In Jesus name. Amen.

